mp, the essays weave together the many cross-currents of religious, intellectual, and literary traditions in medieval China to provide vivid pictures of medieval Chinese religion and culture as it was lived and practiced. The contributors to the volume are all highly regarded experts in the fields of Chinese poetry, Daoism, Buddhism, popular religion, and literature. Their research papers cut across imagined disciplinary boundaries to show that the culture of medieval China can only be understood by close reading of texts from multiple genres, traditions, and approaches.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aDaoism, Buddhism, medieval China, medieval poetry.1 aBokenkamp, Stephen R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampany, Robert Ford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleeman, Terry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKroll, Paul W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLagerwey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPettit, J. E. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaz, Gil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaz, Gil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShields, Anna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShields, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVerellen, Franciscus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZongyu, W